To achieve this, you will need to write a userscript that can monitor various events on the page, including AJAX requests, DOM mutations, and page visibility changes.

Here's an example script that demonstrates how to monitor such events using Greasemonkey or Tampermonkey:

```javascript
// ==UserScript==
// @name     Page Event Logger
// @version  1
// @grant    none
// @include  http://your-target-domain.com/*
// ==/UserScript==

(function() {
    'use strict';

    // This will be used to throttle the logging
    let lastLogTime = 0;
    const throttleTime = 1000; // 1 second throttle

    function logEvent(e) {
        const currentTime = Date.now();
        if (currentTime - lastLogTime > throttleTime) {
            console.log(e.type, 'event detected:', e);
            lastLogTime = currentTime;
        }
    }

    // Monitor AJAX requests
    const origOpen = XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open;
    XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open = function() {
        this.addEventListener('loadstart', logEvent);
        this.addEventListener('progress', logEvent);
        this.addEventListener('load', logEvent);
        this.addEventListener('error', logEvent);
        this.addEventListener('abort', logEvent);
        origOpen.apply(this, arguments);
    };

    // Observe DOM mutations (if needed)
    const observer = new MutationObserver(mutations => {
        mutations.forEach(mutation => {
            logEvent({ type: 'dom-mutation', mutation: mutation });
        });
    });

    // Configuration of the observer:
    const observerConfig = { childList: true, subtree: true };

    // Select the target node
    const targetNode = document.body;

    // Start observing
    observer.observe(targetNode, observerConfig);

    // Monitor page visibility for detecting page refresh or tab close
    document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', () => {
        if (document.hidden) {
            console.log('Page is hidden - could be a prelude to refresh or tab close.');
        } else {
            console.log('Page is visible again.');
        }
    });

    // Detect a full page reload, including manual refresh or redirect
    window.addEventListener('beforeunload', logEvent);
})();
```

Let's break down what this script is doing:
1. It creates a `logEvent` function that only logs an event if it hasn't been logged in the past second, to avoid spamming the console.
2. It intercepts `XMLHttpRequest` to monitor AJAX request events for loading progress including `loadstart`, `progress`, `load`, `error`, and `abort`.
3. It sets up a `MutationObserver` to monitor DOM changes if you want to log when new elements are added or existing ones are removed/changed.
4. It monitors the page's visibility status to infer when a user might be leaving the page or the tab is being closed.
5. It listens to the `beforeunload` event to detect a full page reload or redirect.

In terms of detecting a redirect that logs you out, that's trickier — typically scripts are not informed about why a page is unloading (whether it's a user action, redirect, or script-initiated). However, the `beforeunload` event can still be useful for logging whenever the page is about to be unloaded for any reason.

Remember to change `@include` to the domain you're targeting, and adjust the event listeners and observer according to your specific needs. You might not need to monitor all these events, so you can remove any unnecessary code to keep the script lightweight. Make sure the script runs at `document-start` if you want to catch events that occur immediately as the page loads.

Keep in mind that the actual implementation depends on the exact behavior of the page you're targeting. More complex interactions might require additional or different approaches to monitoring.

If you want to create a function in your Greasemonkey/Tampermonkey script that checks for the presence of an error message using the provided XPath and returns the text content if found, you can use the following function:

```javascript
// ==UserScript==
// @name     Error Message Checker
// @version  1
// @grant    none
// @include  http://your-target-domain.com/*
// ==/UserScript==

(function() {
    'use strict';

    function getErrorMessage() {
        // XPath for the error message
        const xpath = '//*[@id="root"]/div/div/div/div[3]/div[3]/div[1]/div/div/span[2]';
        // Evaluate the XPath to get the first matching node
        const errorNode = document.evaluate(xpath, document, null, XPathResult.FIRST_ORDERED_NODE_TYPE, null).singleNodeValue;

        if (errorNode) {
            // The error node exists
            // Retrieve all text nodes under the error span, including any nested spans
            const textNodes = document.evaluate('.//text()', errorNode, null, XPathResult.ORDERED_NODE_SNAPSHOT_TYPE, null);

            // Concatenate the content of each text node to get the full error message
            let fullText = '';
            for (let i = 0; i < textNodes.snapshotLength; i++) {
                fullText += textNodes.snapshotItem(i).nodeValue.trim() + ' ';
            }

            return fullText.trim(); // Return the trimmed error message
        }

        // If the error node does not exist, return null
        return null;
    }

    // Example usage:
    // This would be placed where you want to check for an error message, such as in an event handler
    const errorMessage = getErrorMessage();
    if (errorMessage) {
        console.log('Error message detected:', errorMessage);
    }
})();
```

Explanation:
1. `getErrorMessage` function uses `document.evaluate` to execute an XPath query that selects the span you mentioned where error messages are expected to appear.
2. If the element is found, it then queries all text nodes (`'.//text()'`) under this span to get both direct text and text within any child spans. The XPath `'.//text()'` means it selects all text nodes that are descendants of the context node (in this case, the error span node).
3. This function concatenates all the text from these nodes and trims the result to form the complete error message.
4. The function returns the error message if one is found or `null` if there is no error.

Remember to modify the `@include` directive to match the URL(s) where your script should run, and you can call `getErrorMessage()` whenever you want to check for an error message, such as in an event listener responding to the page's load events.

