You are correct that the `lastLogTime` variable in my previous example is script-global and will indeed affect the logging of all events, not just individual types of events. If the script logs an event, it will not log another event of any type until one second has passed. This might not be the behavior you intended, especially if you want to throttle each event type individually.

To throttle each type of event separately, you can use a dictionary (JavaScript object) to keep track of the last time each event type was logged. Here's how you can modify the `logEvent` function:

```javascript
// This will be used to throttle the logging by event type
let lastLogTimes = {};

const throttleTime = 1000; // 1 second throttle

function logEvent(e) {
    const currentTime = Date.now();
    // Initialize last log time for the event type if it doesn't exist
    if (!lastLogTimes[e.type]) {
        lastLogTimes[e.type] = 0;
    }
    // Check if enough time has passed since the last event of this type was logged
    if (currentTime - lastLogTimes[e.type] > throttleTime) {
        console.log(e.type, 'event detected:', e);
        lastLogTimes[e.type] = currentTime;
    }
}
```

With these changes, the script will maintain a separate throttle timer for each type of event. It will only prevent logging the same type of event within one second of the last time it was logged. This way, you can avoid spam on a per-event-type basis while still being able to capture all different types of events that occur in rapid succession.

