In JavaScript, event listeners are designed to be cumulative and non-exclusive, meaning multiple event listeners can be added to the same event on the same target without overriding each other. When an event is dispatched, all listeners attached to that event on the target will be called in the order they were added.

So, if you add `this.addEventListener('load', logEvent);` and also have `window.addEventListener("load", createFloatingUI);` elsewhere in your script, and assuming `this` refers to the same object as `window`, both `logEvent` and `createFloatingUI` functions will be invoked when the `load` event triggers. One will not override the other. 

Example:
```javascript
window.addEventListener('load', function() {
    console.log('First load event listener');
});

window.addEventListener('load', function() {
    console.log('Second load event listener');
});
```

When the window's `load` event triggers, the console will log:

```
First load event listener
Second load event listener
```

In your case, with your userscript:

```javascript
window.addEventListener('load', createFloatingUI); // Adds the first load event listener to the window

// ...

// If "this" is another object like XMLHttpRequest, it will have its own context for events
this.addEventListener('load', logEvent); // If "this" is the window, it adds a second listener

// If "this" refers to an instance of XMLHttpRequest, then you're adding a 'load' listener to that specific XMLHttpRequest
// This would not conflict with the window's 'load' event
```

Keep in mind that `this` in JavaScript is context-dependent. In the global scope of a browser script, `this` usually refers to the `window` object. However, inside an event handler, a function, or a method of an object, `this` can point to the object that the function is a property of, which might not be `window`.

It's also worth mentioning that you can remove an event listener at any point using `removeEventListener`, provided you have a reference to the same function that was added initially.

Yes, you can detect when the text within a `<textarea>` element is changed by listening for the `input` event, which fires synchronously whenever the value of the `<textarea>` changes. You can also listen for the `change` event if you want to detect when the user has finished editing and the element loses focus. However, the `input` event is the most commonly used for detecting live changes to the content within form elements like `<input>` and `<textarea>`.

Here is an example of how you can set up an event listener for changes to a `<textarea>` element using an XPath to find the element:

```javascript
// ==UserScript==
// @name     Textarea Change Listener
// @version  1
// @grant    none
// @include  http://your-target-domain.com/*
// ==/UserScript==

(function() {
    'use strict';

    // XPath to find the textarea
    const xpath = '//*[@id="root"]/div/div/div/div[3]/div[2]/div/div/form/div[1]/span/textarea';

    // Use document.evaluate to get the textarea node
    const textAreaNode = document.evaluate(xpath, document, null, XPathResult.FIRST_ORDERED_NODE_TYPE, null).singleNodeValue;

    // Define what to do when the textarea content changes
    function handleTextareaInput(event) {
        console.log('Textarea content changed:', event.target.value);
    }

    // If the element was found, add the 'input' event listener
    if (textAreaNode) {
        textAreaNode.addEventListener('input', handleTextareaInput);
    } else {
        console.error('Textarea element not found');
    }
})();
```

In this script:

1. We use `document.evaluate` with the provided XPath to locate the `<textarea>` element.
2. Once we have a handle on the `<textarea>` node, we attach an event listener to it that listens for `input` events.
3. The `handleTextareaInput` function is defined to act whenever the `input` event fires.

This script should be executed once the DOM is fully loaded. Be aware that if the `<textarea>` element is dynamically added to the page after it loads (for example, by an AJAX request or client-side script operation), you may need to set the event listener after the element has been created, or use a delegated event handler attached to a parent element that is present at the time your script runs. 

Also, note that event listeners should typically be attached to the element node directly, not to the text node within it (`/text()` at the end of the XPath), because the `input` and `change` events are dispatched on the input element itself rather than the text node.

