If you want to check whether the error message contains certain strings, you can use the `String.prototype.includes()` method in JavaScript, which determines whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.

Here's an example of how you might use this with a series of options:

```javascript
const errorMessage = getErrorMessage();

// Define an array of error message options you want to check for
const errorOptions = [
    "first error message fragment",
    "second error message fragment",
    "another error piece",
    "some other text"
];

// Check if errorMessage contains any of the errorOptions
for (const option of errorOptions) {
    if (errorMessage && errorMessage.includes(option)) {
        console.log(`Found an error containing: "${option}"`);
    }
}
```

This example loops over a set of predefined error message options and checks if any of these options are included in the `errorMessage`. If a match is found, it logs to the console that this particular error condition has been detected.

You can extend the `errorOptions` array to include any number of strings you wish to check against the error message. This matching is case-sensitive. If you want a case-insensitive match, you can convert both the `errorMessage` and the `option` to the same case (either upper or lower) before calling `includes`, like so:

```javascript
// Example of case-insensitive matching
if (errorMessage && errorMessage.toLowerCase().includes(option.toLowerCase())) {
    console.log(`Found an error containing: "${option}"`);
}
```

This way, your comparisons won't be affected by differences in casing.

